<body>
<div type="description" n="monument">
<head>Description of Monument</head>
<p>A <rs type="material">white marble</rs> <rs type="objectType">altar-stele</rs> with moulding above and below (<measure dim="height" unit="metre" type="length">0.84</measure> x <measure dim="width" unit="metre" type="length">0.37</measure> x <measure dim="depth" unit="metre" type="length">0.28</measure>). The relief is of a heavily armed <rs type="decoration">gladiator</rs>, with short sword in right hand, long shield in left, and a helmet which obscures his face, advancing right.</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="text">
<head>Description of Text</head>
<p><rs type="execution" key="scalpro">Inscribed</rs> on the face</p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="letters">
<head>Letters</head>
<p>Standard forms; <measure dim="height" type="length" unit="metre">0.02</measure></p>
</div>
<div type="description" n="date">
<head>Date</head>
<p>
<date notBefore="0101" notAfter="0300" exact="none">Second to third centuries A.D.</date>(<rs type="criteria">content</rs>, <rs type="criteria">lettering</rs>)</p>
</div>
<div type="edition" lang="grc">
<head lang="en">Edition</head>
<ab><lb n="1"/> <persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Μαργαρέτης">Μαργαρέτης</name></persName> </ab>
</div>

<div type="translation">
<head>Translation</head>
<p>Margaretes</p>
</div>
<div type="commentary">
<head>Commentary</head>
<p>For the name, 'Pearl', see Sabbatini, Roma no. 54, and D. French, 'Two gladiatorial texts', no.1.</p>
</div>
<div type="history" n="locations">
<head>Locations</head>
<p> <rs type="found">Robert assumed that this altar-stele was found with the others seen by Reichel, <xref type="inscription" n="625" href="120015">12.15</xref>, <xref type="inscription" n="626" href="120013">12.13</xref>, and <xref type="inscription" n="627" href="120016">12.16</xref>, all of which were found near the <rs type="monuList">Stadium</rs>; it is also copied by Kubitschek on an endpaper with <xref type="inscription" n="626" href="120013">12.13</xref> and <xref type="inscription" n="627" href="120016">12.16</xref>. But the location given by Reichel suggests that it was seen south of the <rs type="monuList">Walls, South (east part)</rs>, and should probably therefore be associated with <xref type="inscription" n="629" href="120621">12.621</xref>, <xref type="inscription" n="630" href="120622">12.622</xref>, and <xref type="inscription" n="631" href="120615">12.615</xref>, all found reused in that part of the city wall</rs>
<rs type="origLocation">Unknown</rs>
<rs type="lastLocation">Findspot</rs>
</p>
</div>
<div type="history" n="text-constituted-from">
<head>Text Constituted From</head>
<p>Publications; Reichel notebook</p>
</div>
<div type="history" n="record">
<head>History of Recording</head>

<p>Copied by G. Doublet and G. Deschamps in 1887; copied by Reichel in 1892 'im Felde vor der Südmauer' (R.I.23) and mentioned by Kubitschek (K.III, endpaper); not reported subsequently.</p>
</div>
